IBM Quantum devices¶

  • Launched in 2016 (a 5-qubit device controlled from the browser)
  • Now counts 25 quantum devices from 1 to 65 qubits
  • Devices are accessible from the cloud, using the browser or the Qiskit SDK
  • Free registration gives immediate access to 8 devices and simulators

https://quantum-computing.ibm.com

Gate-based quantum computers¶

Superconducting quantum devices¶

Noise¶

Quantum gate-based devices are characterized by various sources of noise

  • Finite qubit coherence times $T_1$, $T_2$ (interaction with the environment)
  • Gate error rates (imperfect pulses, interaction with env., crosstalk)
  • Measurement errors (discrimination errors, imperfect pulses, crosstalk)

Programming IBM Quantum devices¶

Qiskit https://qiskit.org¶

Qiskit is an open-source Python package developed by IBM. It contains tools for:

  • the design of quantum circuits
  • the simulation of quantum circuits, with and without noise
  • the execution on real devices
  • the characterization and mitigation of noise
  • high-level algorithms that exploit quantum computers

pip install qiskit

Hello world¶

We are going to create a two-qubit Bell state:

$$ |\psi\rangle = \frac{|00\rangle + |11\rangle}{\sqrt{2}}$$

First we are going to design the circuit, then we are going to run it on a real device.

The state vector is in the form $$ c_0 |00\rangle + c_1 |01 \rangle + c_2 |10\rangle + c_3 |11\rangle $$

We bring the first qubit into a superposition state $|+\rangle = (|0\rangle + |1\rangle) / \sqrt{2}$.

We use the Hadamard gate

$$ H = \tfrac{1}{\sqrt{2}}\begin{bmatrix} 1 & 1 \\ 1 & -1 \end{bmatrix} $$

Measurement¶

We do not have access to the quantum state on a real device. We need to perform measurements.

On the IBM devices, we can make a projective measurement onto the computational basis $(\ket{0}, \ket{1})$

In [47]:
qr = QuantumRegister(2, name='q') # The qubits
cr = ClassicalRegister(2, name='c') # The bits for storing the measurement outcome

qc = QuantumCircuit(qr, cr)

qc.h(0)
qc.cx(0, 1)

qc.measure(0, 0)
qc.measure(1, 1)

qc.draw(output='mpl', initial_state=True)

Exercise¶

The fact that we measure '00' and '11' with high probability does not mean that we have prepared an entangled state. The two qubit may simply be classically correlated.

In order to test whether entanglement is present, one should check if the Bell inequalities are violated.

This can be done as an exercise!

Measurement error mitigation¶

The projective measurement of the qubit is a complicated process which involves the attribution of a label (0 or 1) to a measured microwave signal.

There is a certain probability that each qubit is read in the wrong state.

This probability can be easily accounted for. Given $N$ qubits of interest, we can prepare each of the $2^N$ possible basis states, immediately measure them, and see what probability exists for each outcome.

NOTE This is not quantum error correction

In [100]:
# Import measurement calibration functions
from qiskit.ignis.mitigation.measurement import (complete_meas_cal,
                                                 CompleteMeasFitter)
In [101]:
meas_calibs, state_labels = complete_meas_cal(qr=qr, qubit_list=[0, 1, 2], circlabel='mcal')

meas_calibs is a list of circuits where the $N$ qubits are prepared in all $2^N$ vectors of the computational basis and measured.

In [132]:
meas_calibs[2].draw(output='mpl')
Out[132]:

This one prepares $\ket{010}$, for example.

We run the calibration circuits on the device

In [ ]:
calib_job = qiskit.execute(meas_calibs, backend=rome_backend, shots=8192)
In [106]:
calib_job = rome_backend.retrieve_job('604bb28f09a82b3a2d6f1164')
cal_results = calib_job.result()

The results can now be processed with CompleteMeasFitter, which constructs a calibration matrix

In [107]:
meas_fitter = CompleteMeasFitter(cal_results, state_labels, qubit_list=range(3), circlabel='mcal')
# Plot the calibration matrix
meas_fitter.plot_calibration()

The calibration matrix can now be used to mitigate readout errors from other circuits.

In [109]:
meas_filter = meas_fitter.filter
mitigated_counts = meas_filter.apply(ghz_job_2.result()).get_counts()

Tomography¶

We don't have access to the quantum state $\ket{\psi}$.

But we can reconstruct it by performing a suitable set of measurements on multiple copies of the state.

Since noise is present, or we are interested in part of the qubits of the system, we will in general talk about an ensemble state, described by the density operator $\rho$.

Tomography of a qubit¶

The density operator of a qubit can be written as

$$ \rho = \frac 12 (\mathbb{I} + a_x \sigma_x + a_y \sigma_y + a_z \sigma_z) $$

and $a_x = \text{Tr}[\rho \sigma_x] = \langle \sigma_x \rangle$ etc.

In [310]:
plot_bloch_vector([1, 0, 0])
Out[310]:

By measuring $\langle \sigma_x \rangle$, $\langle \sigma_y \rangle$, $\langle \sigma_z \rangle$, we can reconstruct $\rho$.

IBM devices measure projections along $\sigma_z$. How do we measure the other expectation values?

Notice that simply writing $\rho = \frac 12 \left(\mathbb{I} + \langle \sigma_x \rangle \sigma_x + \langle \sigma_y \rangle \sigma_y + \langle \sigma_z \rangle \sigma_z\right)$ may give non-physical density operators.

Other techniques are used, for example maximum-likelihood reconstruction.

For two qubits, we need to measure all possible combinations $\langle \sigma_x \otimes \sigma_x \rangle, \langle \sigma_x \otimes \sigma_y \rangle, \ldots, \langle \sigma_z \otimes \sigma_z \rangle$ and so on.

Example: tomography of the Bell state¶

The Bell state is $\ket{\psi} = (\ket{00} + \ket{11})/\sqrt{2}$. The corresponding density matrix is

$$\rho = \ket{\psi}\bra{\psi} = \begin{pmatrix} \frac 12 & 0 & 0 & \frac 12 \\ 0 & 0 & 0 & 0 \\ 0 & 0 & 0 & 0 \\ \frac 12 & 0 & 0 & \frac 12 \end{pmatrix}$$
In [341]:

qc.h(0)
qc.cx(0, 1)
qc.draw(output='mpl', initial_state=True)

Grover search¶

Finds a marked item in a list of $N$ items in $O(\sqrt{N})$ iterations.

Offers a quadratic speed-up compared to classical search.

Example¶

Let's run the grover search on a list of 8 elements. The elements can be encoded in 3 qubits.

Let's assume that the correct answer is 101.

So we have a oracle function $f(101) = 1$ and $f(x) = 0$ elsewhere.

Open quantum systems with IBM Quantum¶

We can use IBM devices as quantum simulators.

We used the IBM devices to simulate open quantum dynamics:

  • Amplitude damping channel
  • Depolarizing channel
  • Pauli channel
  • Reservoir engineering
  • Collisional models

Depolarizing channel¶

With probability $1-p$ the qubit remains intact, with probability $p$ becomes maximally mixed

The circuit to implement the channel

The rotation angle for the $R_y$ gates depends on the value of $p$.

A tomographic reconstruction of $\rho_S$ for various values of $p$

Take-home messages¶

  • Current quantum computers are limited by noise and connectivity layout
  • We can't use them as universal quantum computers
  • We need to design the circuits by hand to minimize the number of gates
  • We can still use them as quantum simulators for research and for near-term applications (see Guille's lecture)
